          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which of the following correctly describes the composition of the basement membr</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following correctly describes the composition of the basement membrane?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Type I collagen, fibronectin, and chondroitin sulphate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Type I collagen is found in bone, skin, and tendon — not in the basement membrane. Fibronectin is an adhesive glycoprotein and chondroitin sulphate is a GAG of the interstitial matrix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Elastin, hyaluronic acid, and tenascin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Elastin provides recoil in arteries and lungs, and hyaluronic acid is a free GAG chain in the interstitial matrix. Neither is a defining basement membrane component.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Type IV collagen, laminin, and perlecan</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The basement membrane is a thin, specialised ECM layer beneath all epithelial and endothelial cells. It is specifically rich in type IV collagen (structural framework), laminin (organises BM structure), and perlecan (a heparan sulphate proteoglycan).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Type III collagen, entactin, and keratan sulphate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Type III collagen supports blood vessels and the gut (interstitial matrix). While entactin is an adhesive glycoprotein associated with basement membranes, the defining triad taught here is type IV collagen, laminin, and perlecan.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The basement membrane is specifically composed of type IV collagen, laminin, and perlecan. This distinguishes it from the interstitial matrix, which contains type I and III collagens."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The basement membrane sits beneath all epithelial and endothelial cells and is characterised by type IV collagen, laminin, and the proteoglycan perlecan."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
