          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which step of collagen synthesis is specifically impaired in scurvy due to vitam</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which step of collagen synthesis is specifically impaired in scurvy due to vitamin C deficiency?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Translation of pro-alpha chains on rough endoplasmic reticulum</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Pro-alpha chain translation is the first step of collagen synthesis and proceeds normally without vitamin C.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hydroxylation of proline and lysine residues</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) keeps iron in its reduced ferrous state, which is essential for prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase activity. Without hydroxylation, collagen cannot form a stable triple helix, resulting in the clinical features of scurvy.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cleavage of propeptides to form tropocollagen</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Propeptide cleavage occurs extracellularly and does not require vitamin C. Failure of this step causes dermatosparaxis, a form of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Oxidative cross-linking of lysine residues by lysyl oxidase</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lysyl oxidase requires copper, not vitamin C. Deficiency of copper — as in Menkes disease — impairs this final cross-linking step.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Vitamin C deficiency specifically impairs hydroxylation of proline and lysine. Without hydroxyproline and hydroxylysine, the collagen triple helix is unstable — this is the molecular basis of scurvy."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Vitamin C is essential for the hydroxylation step — it maintains iron in its ferrous form so that prolyl and lysyl hydroxylase can function."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
