          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A child presents with coarse facial features, corneal clouding, and hepatospleno</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A child presents with coarse facial features, corneal clouding, and hepatosplenomegaly. Enzyme assay reveals deficiency of alpha-L-iduronidase. Which glycosaminoglycans accumulate in this condition?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Keratan sulphate and chondroitin sulphate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Keratan sulphate accumulates in Morquio syndrome (MPS IVA) due to N-acetylgalactosamine-6-sulphatase deficiency, not alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Heparan sulphate and dermatan sulphate</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This is Hurler syndrome (MPS I). Alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency leads to accumulation of both heparan sulphate and dermatan sulphate, causing coarse facies, corneal clouding, hepatosplenomegaly, intellectual disability, and cardiac valve disease.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hyaluronic acid and heparin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hyaluronic acid is not degraded via the lysosomal pathway affected in mucopolysaccharidoses. Heparin is produced by mast cells and is not a storage product in any classical MPS.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Chondroitin sulphate and heparan sulphate</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While heparan sulphate does accumulate in Hurler syndrome, it is dermatan sulphate — not chondroitin sulphate — that is the other accumulating GAG in alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "This presentation describes Hurler syndrome (MPS I). Alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency causes accumulation of heparan sulphate and dermatan sulphate — remember this combination as the hallmark of MPS I."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Hurler syndrome (MPS I) results from alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency, leading to accumulation of heparan and dermatan sulphate."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
